This paper discusses the generalization ability of deep neural networks, which is a common topic in the machine learning community. The paper specifically focuses on the margin dynamics of neural networks, which is related to the optimization and training of the models. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), followed by cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) and cs.CV (Computer Vision). The paper also discusses the expressive power of models and the complexity of data, which are related to the theoretical aspects of machine learning, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) a likely sub-category as well. Finally, the paper proposes a novel method to predict the trend of generalization or test error, which involves statistical analysis and complexity theory, making cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) a possible sub-category.
